Automatic Mop
Jagrat Patel & Lav Patel
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
The report details the development of
Automatic Mop. This project will be used for automatic
cleaning of domestic and industrial surfaces. When turned on,
it cleans the floor by shaking the entire surface (such as the
ground). The control unit is used to drive the engine and is
connected to sensors to avoid obstacles. It helps to improve
the human lifestyle.
Key Words: Microcontroller, Motor Driver, Ultrasonic
Sensor.
1.INTRODUCTION
Recently, you need an automatic floor cleaner. Therefore,
Auto-mop is designed to clean the surroundings, and
installing a cleaning device can save human effort. This
report focuses on designing and planning of our automop.
There is a dedicated moping system created for cleaning the
floor with not a vacuum but with our water mop system.
Ultrasonic sensors are used to detect obstacles and turn
around during movement to prevent the robot from falling
or from hitting the obstacle.
1.1 SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE
Microcontroller (Arduino Uno) is used to control all motors
and sensors. DC motors attached to motor drivers to
provide high current and most importantly it is installed
with a sensor and a water dripper which gives little amount
of water for cleaning. For Power Supply two separate
batteries are used. Both are used to full fill the power
requirement.
A. Hardware used:
a) Arduino Uno
b) Ultrasonic sensor (SC-H04)
c) Motor driver (L293D)
Arduino Uno:
The Arduino Uno is an ATmega328 based
microcontroller board. It has 14 digital I/O ports (6 inputs
usable as PWM outputs), 6 analog inputs, a 16 MHz crystal
oscillator, USB connection, power connection, ICSP header,
and a reset button. It contains everything you need to
support your microcontroller. To get started, plug it into
your computer or power it with a DC adapter or battery.
One differs from all previous cards in that it does not use
the FTDI USB to Serial driver chip. Instead, I have an
Atmega8U2 programmed as a USB-to-serial converter.
Ultrasonic sensor (SC-H04):
The HC-SR04 ultrasonic ranging module provides non-
contact measurement performance from 2cm to 400cm,
and the distance accuracy can reach 3mm. The device
consists of a transmitter, a receiver and an control circuit.
The basic principle of work:
(1) Using IO trigger for at least 10us high level signal.
(2) The Module automatically sends eight 40 kHz and
detect whether there is a pulse signal back.
(3) IF the signal back, through high level , time of high
output IO duration is the time from sending ultrasonic
to returning. Test distance = (high level time) * (velocity
of sound (340M/S) / 2.
Motor driver (L293D):
a) L293D is rated at 0.65A per bridge (1.20A peak)
with thermal shutdown protection, Motor Voltages
from 4.5VDC to 16VDC. (up to 36V if C6 and C7 are
upgraded)
b) Up to 4 bi-directional DC motors with individual
8-bit speed selection (256 speeds)
c) Up to 2 stepper motors (unipolar or bipolar)
d) Pull down resistors keep motors disabled during
power-up
e) Separate Logic and Motor power connections
f) Terminal block connectors for motors and power
g) 2 connections for 5V 'hobby' servos
B. Software Description
Arduino programming uses the Arduino IDE, a free
program that lets you program in a language that Arduino
understands. For Arduino, this language is based on C/C++
and can also be extended using C++ libraries. You can use
the IDE to create a computer program that consists of a
series of step-by-step instructions that are loaded into an
Arduino. The Arduino executes these commands and
communicates with the person it is connected to. In the
Arduino world, programs are called " sketches".
1.2 Sample circuit
1.3 Logic for movement
The automatic floor cleaner is intelligently programmed to
clean a specific area through a mopping system. The cleaner
is cost effective, convenient, environment friendly that
saves the valuable time of any person. DC motor is used to
change direction of wheels which is connected to the
platform. If the enough current is produced then DC motors
can be operated directly otherwise a motor driver is
required so as to provide it a high current i.e. upto 0.7 to 1.2
ampere. Driver Used is named as L293D with H-Bridge
Configuration. The cleaner is handy and can spin anywhere
in any direction.
Sensors are basically used to set up a communication link
between the outside world and the digital device and to
fulfil the purpose use two Ultrasonic Sensors (HC-SR04) are
incorporated in the project. One of it is used to detect the
obstacles or hurdles in front of the cleaner so it moves back
and change its path or lane and the other is used to detect
the height in order to prevent the cleaner from falling down.
A self-build mop unit is attached to the brushless DC motor
rotating at a very high speed.
2. FUTURE SCOPE
Currently, 95% of floor cleaning costs are borne by
workers. The high cost of this simple task is the continued
development of alternative solutions such as automatic
floor vacuums. Home automatic floor cleaners are used in
industry and have become an important part of life, saving
time and money and greatly reducing labour costs. The cost
is about 3,000 rupees. This is the future of cleaning in a
fast-paced life. Naturally, it is more reliable than manual
traction.

4.CONCLUSIONS
This study enables efficient floor cleaning. The floor
cleaner is integrated into the design with various
components such as DC motors and ultrasonic sensors,
making it easy to use and save time and convenience when
cleaning at home or at work. With a simple algorithm and
software. Manual cleaning may not be as effective as
picking everything up because you can't see it, but an
automatic floor cleaner can easily do it.
